 pandemic=2C how people are managing grief online during lockdown=2C and w=
hat it will take to get us back outside. Get your friends to sign up here=
 (https://forms.technologyreview.com/the-download/) to get The Download ev=
ery day.

How to manage a pandemic

My first taste of coronavirus panic came early one morning in January. An=
 email with the heading =E2=80=98Important Information: Please Read=E2=80=
=99 arrived from our son=E2=80=99s elementary school. The parents of one o=
f his teachers=2C who had recently returned from China=2C had been infecte=
d=E2=80=94Singapore=E2=80=99s cases 8 and 9=2C as it turned out=E2=80=94an=
d the teacher in question was being quarantined.

Singapore was among the first countries to suffer an outbreak (https://www=
=2Etechnologyreview.com/?_thumbnail_id=3D999272&p=3D999117&preview=3Dtrue&tr=
uid=3De1c81eff8f508ac58ea6e03b0cf524e0&utm_source=3Dthe_download&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_ca=
mpaign=3Dthe_download.unpaid.engagement&utm_content=3D04-14-2020) . In the=
 months since=2C it has been at once reassuring and unnerving to watch its=
 journey from an early hotspot to a kind of haven state=2C holding out dog=
gedly against an invader that has infiltrated so many others.

Early commentary in the West focused on the failings of China=E2=80=99s au=
tocratic system=2C which hid the severity of Wuhan=E2=80=99s outbreak=E2=
=80=94at what we now know to be catastrophic cost. The more the epidemic h=
as spread=2C the more it has become clear that Western liberal democracies=
 have badly mishandled it too=2C ending up with severe outbreaks that coul=
d=E2=80=94perhaps=E2=80=94have been avoided.

Yet it makes little sense to view the coronavirus as some kind of perverse=
 vitality test for liberal and authoritarian regimes. Instead we should le=
arn from the countries that responded more effectively=E2=80=94namely=2C A=
sia=E2=80=99s advanced technocratic democracies. In the West the virus exp=
osed creaking public services and political division. But Hong Kong=2C Jap=
an=2C and South Korea have managed better=2C while Singapore and Taiwan ha=
ve kept the disease almost entirely under control=2C at least for now. Rea=
d the full story by James Crabtree (https://www.technologyreview.com/?_thu=
mbnail_id=3D999272&p=3D999117&preview=3Dtrue&truid=3De1c81eff8f508ac58ea6e03b0cf524e0&utm_=
source=3Dthe_download&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3Dthe_download.unpai=
d.engagement&utm_content=3D04-14-2020) .

The lonely reality of grieving online during social isolation

A grim trend: The global coronavirus pandemic has forced people to think a=
bout death=2C while simultaneously upending the ways in which we are used=
 to experiencing grief and loss. The only option is to grieve online (http=
s://www.technologyreview.com/2020/04/13/999348/covid-19-grief-zoom-funeral=
s/?truid=3De1c81eff8f508ac58ea6e03b0cf524e0&utm_source=3Dthe_download&utm_medium=3Demail&u=
tm_campaign=3Dthe_download.unpaid.engagement&utm_content=3D04-14-2020) .

Not new: The coronavirus pandemic didn=E2=80=99t create online mourning an=
d grief. Facebook groups already connect mothers grieving young children t=
o each other=2C and social-media profiles often become memorials. Live-str=
eaming=2C too=2Cis already a part of how people grieve. (https://www.wired=
=2Ecom/story/funerals-livestreamed-families-grateful/) Well before coronavir=
us sent billions of people into lockdown=2C there were reasons not everybo=
dy could make it to a funeral.

An added pain: The covid-19 pandemic has forced all those dealing with dea=
th to confront the possibility that they won=E2=80=99t be able to access w=
hat mourners may need most: human touch=2C connection=2C and community sup=
port. Read the full story (https://www.technologyreview.com/2020/04/13/999=
348/covid-19-grief-zoom-funerals/?truid=3De1c81eff8f508ac58ea6e03b0cf524e0&utm_source=3Dth=
e_download&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_campaign=3Dthe_download.unpaid.engagemen=
t&utm_content=3D04-14-2020) .

=E2=80=94Abby Ohlheiser

This is what it will take to get us back outside

We have to prepare for a world in which there is no cure and no vaccine fo=
r a long time.

There is a way to live in this world without staying permanently shut indo=
ors. But it won=E2=80=99t be a return to normal; this will be=2C for Weste=
rners at any rate=2C a new normal.

It will entail a considerable degree of surveillance and social controls.=
 It will also create or exacerbate divisions between haves and have-nots.

This new social order will seem unthinkable to most people in so-called fr=
ee countries. But any change can quickly become normal if people accept it=
=2E Getting to normal=2C therefore=2C is not so much about getting back the=
 old normality as it is about getting back the ability to know what is goi=
ng to happen tomorrow. MIT Technology Review=E2=80=99s editor in chief Gid=
eon Lichfield=2C has the full story (https://technologyreview.us11.list-ma=
nage.com/track/click?u=3D47c1a9cec9749a8f8cbc83e78&id=3Df77bb4e1de&e=3D488=
c2c6a6b) on what a post-coronavirus future might look like.

Tune into a new episode of Radio Corona (https://slack-redir.net/link?url=
=3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Fforms.technologyreview.com%2Fradio-corona%2F) at 2pm ET t=
oday.
Jennifer Strong=2C our audio and live journalism editor=2C will speak with=
 economist John Van Reenen about how to make effective policy to salvage t=
he global economy. It will also be available on our Facebook page (https:/=
